title: Region 1 wrestling: Tenafly cinderella, Ramapo underdog still alive in quarterfinals
text:
Region homepages 
The first round of the NJSIAA Region 1 Tournament wrapped up Wednesday night at Bergen Community College in Paramus as 56 wrestlers advanced to the quarterfinals to keep their Atlantic City hopes alive while another 56 wrestlers saw their seasons come to end. 
Below are some highlights. 
The Kwondary : Tenafly senior Timothy Kwon is proving he is quite the darkhorse. Despite drawing the No. 7 seed, Kwon advanced out of District 2 as a third-place finisher. Now, the heavyweight is still alive and heading to the quarterfinals after earning a 5-3 decision over West Milford’s Eric Lindstrom. Kwon, arguably one of the biggest cinderella stories in the state, will try to keep his run going against Drew Flynn of Pompton Lakes, a champion out of District 4. 
Upset of the night : Despite trailing 4-0 in the third period, Ramapo’s Luke Brantly found a way to eliminate a Hunterdon/Warren/Sussex champion. Brantly chose neutral to start the third period and pinned Kittatinny’s Shane Smith to advance to the 160-pound quarterfinals. Brantly, a sophomore who is 24-16, will face District 2 champion Reece Mulduun next. 
Wayne Hills trifecta : All four qualifiers from Wayne Hills were in action in the first round and all four advanced to the quarterfinals, including three wrestlers in a row from 182-220. At 182, Justin Ramirez earned a 7-1 decision over Ramsey’s Ross Woods while Christopher Buzelli and Pete Dellechiaie both won by fall at 195 and 220, respectively. Anthony Rua (138( was another first-round winner for the Patriots. 
To the wire : One of the most exciting matches of the night was between Old Tappan’s Ryan Foy and Sparta’s Paddy Finnegan at 170. In a back-and-forth bout, Foy got a takedown in rideouts to earn an 8-6 decision. The prize? A pairing with Don Bosco’s Dom Mandarino, a two-time state medalist in the quarterfinals.
